            <section class="prose">
              <h2>Simple interest formula</h2>
              <p>
                Simple interest is interest calculated only on the original
                principal, not on previously earned interest. It is common in
                short-term loans, some bonds, and many classroom examples.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Core formulas:</p>
                <p><strong>Interest:</strong> \( I = P \times r \times t \)</p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Final amount:</strong> \( A = P + I = P \times (1 + r
                  \times t) \)
                </p>
                <ul class="mt-2">
                  <li><strong>P</strong> = principal (starting amount)</li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>r</strong> = annual interest rate (in decimal form,
                    e.g. 5% = 0.05)
                  </li>
                  <li><strong>t</strong> = time in years</li>
                  <li><strong>I</strong> = interest earned or paid</li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>A</strong> = final amount (principal + interest)
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>Rearranged formulas</h3>
              <p>
                You can solve the simple interest equation for any variable:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Principal:</strong> \( P = \dfrac{I}{r \times t} =
                  \dfrac{A}{1 + r \times t} \)
                </li>
                <li><strong>Rate:</strong> \( r = \dfrac{I}{P \times t} \)</li>
                <li><strong>Time:</strong> \( t = \dfrac{I}{P \times r} \)</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How to use the simple interest calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose what you want to find</strong> using the tabs:
                  <em>Interest &amp; Final Amount</em>, <em>Principal</em>,
                  <em>Rate</em>, or <em>Time</em>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter the known values</strong>:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Principal (loan amount or investment)</li>
                    <li>Annual interest rate (as % or decimal)</li>
                    <li>Time and its unit (years, months, or days)</li>
                    <li>
                      Or, for reverse calculations, enter interest or final
                      amount.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Select the scenario</strong> (investment or loan) to
                  adjust the wording in the explanation.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Click “Calculate”</strong> to see:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Simple interest (I)</li>
                    <li>Final amount (A)</li>
                    <li>Principal, rate, and time summary</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Optionally tick
                  <strong>“Show step-by-step calculation”</strong> to see the
                  formula with your numbers plugged in.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>
                Suppose you invest $5,000 at 4% simple interest for 3 years. How
                much interest will you earn, and what is the final amount?
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Principal \( P = 5{,}000 \)</li>
                <li>Rate \( r = 4\% = 0.04 \)</li>
                <li>Time \( t = 3 \) years</li>
              </ol>
              <p>Compute the interest:</p>
              <p>
                \[ I = P \times r \times t = 5{,}000 \times 0.04 \times 3 = 600
                \]
              </p>
              <p>Compute the final amount:</p>
              <p>\[ A = P + I = 5{,}000 + 600 = 5{,}600 \]</p>
              <p>
                So you earn <strong>$600</strong> in interest, and your
                investment grows to <strong>$5,600</strong>.
              </p>

              <h2>Converting months and days to years</h2>
              <p>
                The simple interest formula uses time in years. The calculator
                converts other units automatically:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Months to years:</strong> \( t_{\text{years}} =
                  \dfrac{\text{months}}{12} \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Days (365-day year):</strong> \( t_{\text{years}} =
                  \dfrac{\text{days}}{365} \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Days (360-day year):</strong> \( t_{\text{years}} =
                  \dfrac{\text{days}}{360} \) (often used in banking)
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Simple interest vs. compound interest</h2>
              <p>
                With <strong>simple interest</strong>, interest is always
                calculated on the original principal. With
                <strong>compound interest</strong>, interest is periodically
                added to the balance so that future interest is earned on
                interest as well.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Simple interest grows in a straight line over time.</li>
                <li>
                  Compound interest grows faster, especially over long periods.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Many short-term loans and some bonds use simple interest;
                  savings accounts usually use compound interest.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

