                    the rate you enter is annual and converts your time input
                    (months or days) into years automatically.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="faq-question w-full flex justify-between items-center px-4 py-3 text-left"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800"
                      >Can simple interest be negative?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="faq-answer px-4 pb-3 hidden text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    In typical loans and investments, the interest rate is
                    positive, so the interest amount is positive. However, if
                    you model fees or penalties as “negative interest,” you
                    could use a negative rate in the formula. The calculator
                    will accept negative rates, but in real contracts you should
                    rely on the exact terms provided by the lender or
                    institution.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="faq-question w-full flex justify-between items-center px-4 py-3 text-left"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800"
                      >When should I use simple interest instead of compound
                      interest?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="faq-answer px-4 pb-3 hidden text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Use simple interest when the contract or problem explicitly
                    states that interest is simple, or when interest is
                    calculated only on the original principal for the entire
                    period. This is common for short-term personal loans, some
                    car loans, and many textbook exercises. For savings
                    accounts, mortgages, and most long-term investments,
                    compound interest is more appropriate.
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
